Project 7¶

Like previous project assignments, please don't forget to submit your .ipynb and .html files to Canvas.

A hospital in Philadelphia is trying to better streamline its operations and plan for the future by reducing the number hospitalizations that could have been prevented. They have approached you, a data scientist, to help predict if patients will develop heart diseases so that healthcare providers have a chance to intervene much earlier. For this task, you have been provided with the Heart dataset, containing a binary outcome 'HD' that indicates the presence of heart disease in 303 patients. There are 13 predictors including 'Age', 'Sex', 'Chol' (a cholesterol measurement), and other heart and lung function measurements.

# Enter your code here
precision_list = []
recall_list = []
accuracy_list = []

for i in range(3,21):
    
    #Creating the tree classifier
    clf = tree.DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth = i, random_state = 42)
    fit = clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
    
    #Generating the current conf_matrix
    conf_matrix = confusion_matrix(y_test,clf.predict(X_test))
    
    #Assigning the values
    precision = conf_matrix[0][0] / sum(conf_matrix[0])
    recall = conf_matrix[0][0] / (conf_matrix[0][0] + conf_matrix[1][0])
    accuracy = clf.score(X_test, y_test)
    
    #Appending
    precision_list.append(precision)
    recall_list.append(recall)
    accuracy_list.append(accuracy)

#Storing accuracy scores in a list
bag_accuracy_list = []

for i in np.arange(10,50):
    
    #Re-fiting the original model with the n_esimtators hyperparameter re-callibrated to the value of (i)
    bag.set_params(n_estimators = i)
    bag_updated = bag.fit(X_train, y_train)
    
    #Calculating the accuracy score
    accuracy = bag_updated.score(X_test, y_test)
    
    #Storing the accuracy score and the value (i)
    bag_accuracy_list.append([accuracy , i])

Hint:

  1. In this question, we would like to tune only the parameters determining the depth of a tree and the number of trees. But beware that you can also adjust the maximum number of features considered for each tree(max_features), the minimum number of data points placed in a node before the node is split(min_samples_split), the minimum number of data points allowed in a leaf node(min_samples_leaf), and bootstrap option. Refer to sklearn.RandomForestClassifier for a complete list.
  2. In this question, your parameter search space is (3,21) for tree depth, (10,30) for number of trees.
In [41]:
#Defining the search space
search_space = (3,21)

#Storing the names of the hyperparameters we want to optimize in a dictionary:
params = {'max_depth': search_space, 'n_estimators': search_space}

#Using the RandomizedSearchCV function to optimize the specified paramters
rs = RandomizedSearchCV(RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42), param_distributions = params, scoring = 'accuracy')

#Fitting the model
model = rs.fit(X_train, y_train)

#Finding precision, recall, and accuracy scores
rf_tuned_precision = precision_score(y_test, model.predict(X_test))
rf_tuned_recall = recall_score(y_test, model.predict(X_test))
rf_tuned_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, model.predict(X_test))

#Storing best performing parameters:
rf_tuned = rs.best_params_
